<section xml:id="double-angle_and_half-angle_formulas">
  <title>Double-Angle and Half-Angle Formulas</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Suppose we want to accurately position the Hawaiian Star Compass on the Unit Circle. In <xref ref="star-compass-32-compass-rose"/>,the house for Manu is located at halfway between Hikina and ʻĀkau, resulting in an angle of <m>45^{\circ}</m>. By applying right triangle trigonometry, we can determine the exact coordinates of Manu as <m>\left(\cos(45^{\circ}), \sin(45^{\circ})\right) = \left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)</m>. However, as we move to the house of ʻĀina, located halfway between Manu and Hikina, we encounter a problem. The angle for ʻĀina is <m>22.5^{\circ}</m>, which is not explicitly listed listed in <xref ref="tab_trig-table"/>. Therefore, we must resort to a calculator for numerical approximations.
     </p>
     <image xml:id="fig-quad1-Koolau-manu-aina-angles" width="80%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=6.75]
        % draw the coordinates
        \draw[dashed] (0cm,0cm) -- (0.73cm,0cm);
        \draw[-stealth,dashed] (0.97cm,0cm) -- (1.05cm,0cm);
        \draw[dashed] (0cm,0cm) -- (0cm,0.76cm);
        \draw[-stealth,dashed] (0cm,0.98cm) -- (0cm,1.05cm);
        % draw the unit circle
        \draw[thick] (0:1cm) arc (0:90:1cm);
        \draw[left] (0:0.98) node[rotate=0] {\large HIKINA};
        \draw[left] (90:0.98) node[rotate=90] {\large `\={A}KAU};
        \draw (0:1.05) node[right] {$\left(\cos0^{\circ},\sin0^{\circ}\right)=(1,0)$};
        \draw (22.5:1.05) node[right] {$\left(\cos22.5^{\circ},\sin22.5^{\circ}\right)=(?,?)$};
        \draw (45:1.05) node[right] {$\left(\cos45^{\circ},\sin45^{\circ}\right)=\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)$};
        \draw (90:1.05) node[right] {$\left(\cos90^{\circ},\sin90^{\circ}\right)=(0,1)$};
        \foreach \x/\xtext in {
        22.5/{`\={A}ina, $22.5^{\circ}$},
        45/{Manu, $45^{\circ}$}
        }
        \draw[left] (\x:0.98) node[rotate=\x] {\xtext};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
    In this section, we will learn about the double and half-angle formulas for trigonometry. These formulas allow us to determine exact trigonometric function values for angles that are double or half of known values. This will enable us to use our existing knowledge of trigonometric functions at <m>45^{\circ}</m> and apply the half-angle formulas to obtain exact values at <m>22.5^{\circ}</m>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Double-Angle Formulas</title>
    <p>
      Recall the addition formula for sine:
      <men xml:id="eq_double-angle1">
        \sin (\alpha+\beta)=\sin \alpha \cos \beta + \cos \alpha \sin \beta
      </men>
    </p>
    <p>
      Consider the case when the two angles are equal. We will call this angle <m>\theta</m>, so let <m>\alpha=\theta</m> and <m>\beta=\theta</m>.
      Then <xref ref="eq_double-angle1">Eq</xref> becomes
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin(\theta+\theta)\amp = \sin \theta \cos \theta + \cos \theta \sin \theta</mrow>
        <mrow>\sin (2\theta)\amp = 2\sin \theta \cos \theta</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus we obtain a formula for sine of twice the angle <m>\theta</m>.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-double-angle-formula">
      <title>Double-Angle Formulas</title><idx><h>double-angle formulas</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \sin 2\theta \amp = 2\sin \theta \cos \theta</mrow>
            <mrow> \cos 2\theta \amp = \cos^2 \theta - \sin^2 \theta</mrow>
            <mrow> \cos 2\theta \amp = 1-2\sin^2 \theta</mrow>
            <mrow> \cos 2\theta \amp = 2\cos^2 \theta-1</mrow>
            <mrow> \tan 2\theta \amp =  \frac{2\tan \theta}{1-\tan^2 \theta}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      The proofs for the Double-Angle Formulas for Cosine and Tangent are left as exercises (<xref ref="exer-prove-double-angle-cos1"/>-<xref ref="exer-prove-double-angle-tan"/>).
    </p>
    <remark>
      <p>
        Notice that there are three variations of the double-angle formula for cosine. All three equations give the correct answer; however, one version may be more convenient depending on the given information. For example, if you are given the value of <m>\sin\theta</m>, it may be easier to select the version that solely involves <m>\sin\theta</m> and does not include <m>\cos\theta</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <example xml:id="ex_double-angle">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Given <m>\sin\theta=-\frac{5}{13}</m> and <m>\theta</m> lies in Quadrant III, find the exact value of
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sin(2\theta)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            By the double-angle formula, we have <m>\sin(2\theta)=2\sin\theta\cos\theta</m>. We are given the value of <m>\sin\theta</m>, but we do not have <m>\cos\theta</m>. To find <m>\cos\theta</m>, we will draw the triangle formed from <m>\sin\theta=-\frac{5}{13}</m> where <m>\theta</m> lies in Quadrant III.
          </p>
          <image xml:id="fig-example-double-angle-5-12-13">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (-13,0)--(1,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-6)--(0,1) node[above]{\(y\)};
              \draw[line width=1pt] (0,0) -- (-12,0) node[midway,above]{-x};
              \draw[line width=1pt] (-12,0) -- (-12,-5) node[midway,left]{-5};
              \draw[line width=1pt] (-12,-5) -- (0,0) node[midway,below]{13};
              \draw (180:2) arc (180:202.619864948:2) node[midway, left,xshift=-4,yshift=-3] {\(\theta\)};
              \draw (-11,0) -- (-11,-1) -- (-12,-1);
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            Using the Pythagorean Theorem, we can solve the triangle:
            <md>
              <mrow>x^2+(-5)^2\amp = 13^2</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2+25\amp = 169</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2\amp = 144</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp = 12</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            Thus we have
            <me>
              \cos\theta=\frac{\mbox{adjacent}}{\mbox{hypotenuse}}=-\frac{12}{13}
            </me>
            and
            <me>
              \tan\theta=\frac{\mbox{opposite}}{\mbox{adjacent}}=\frac{5}{12}
            </me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            With this new information, we can use the double-angle formula to find <m>\sin(2\theta)</m>:
            <me>
              \sin(2\theta)=2\sin\theta\cos\theta=2\left(-\frac{5}{13}\right)\left(-\frac{12}{13}\right)=\frac{120}{169}
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\cos(2\theta)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To compute <m>\cos2\theta</m>, notice there are three different formulas: <m>\cos2\theta=\cos^\theta-\sin^2\theta</m>, <m>\cos2\theta=1-2\sin^2\theta</m>, or <m>\cos2\theta=2\cos^2\theta-1</m>. Using any of the three equations will give us the correct answer. However, given that we know <m>\sin\theta=-\frac{5}{13}</m>, it may be easier to use <m>\cos2\theta=1-2\sin^2\theta</m>, since the other two equations require us to know <m>\cos\theta</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Without having to draw the triangle, we could get
            <md>
              <mrow> \cos2\theta \amp= 1-2\sin^2\theta </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = 1-2\left(-\frac{5}{13}\right)^2 </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = 1-2\left(\frac{25}{169}\right) </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{169}{169}-\frac{50}{169} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{119}{169} </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\tan(2\theta)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Using the double-angle formula for tangent, we get
            <md>
              <mrow> \tan2\theta \amp =\frac{2\tan\theta}{1-\tan^2\theta} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{2\left(\frac{5}{12}\right)}{1-\left(\frac{5}{12}\right)^2} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{\frac{10}{12}}{1-\frac{25}{144}} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{\frac{10}{12}}{\frac{119}{144}} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{10}{12}\cdot\frac{144}{119}</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{120}{119} </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </example>
