    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write <m>\cos(3\theta)</m> in terms of <m>\sin\theta</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin(3\theta)\amp =\sin(2\theta+\theta)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\sin(2\theta)\cos\theta+\cos(2\theta)\sin\theta\amp \amp \mbox{addition formula}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =(2\sin\theta\cos\theta)\cos\theta+(\cos^2\theta-\sin^2\theta)\sin\theta\amp \amp \mbox{double-angle formula}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =2\sin\theta\cos^2\theta+\sin\theta\cos^2\theta-\sin^3\theta</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =3\sin\theta\cos^2\theta-\sin^3\theta</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =3\sin\theta(1-\sin^2\theta)-\sin^3\theta\amp \amp \mbox{Pythagorean Identity}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =3\sin\theta-3\sin^3\theta-\sin^3\theta</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =3\sin\theta-4\sin^3\theta</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Reducing Powers Formulas</title>
    <p>
      You may notice that the double-angle formula for cosine expresses a trigonometric function in terms of the square of another trigonometric function. By rearranging the terms, we can derive formulas for reducing the powers of sine, cosine, and tangent expressions with even powers to terms involving only cosine. These formulas are particularly useful in calculus.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-formula-reducing-powers">
      <title>Formulas for Reducing Powers</title><idx><h>reducing powers formulas</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <me>
            \sin^2\theta=\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}
          </me>
          <me>
            \cos^2\theta=\frac{1+\cos(2\theta)}{2}
          </me>
          <me>
            \tan^2\theta=\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{1+\cos(2\theta)}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        To prove the first formula, solve for <m>\sin^2\theta</m> in the double-angle formula: <m>\cos2\theta=1-2\sin^2\theta</m>. The second formula is obtained similarly by solving for <m>\cos^2\theta</m> in the formula: <m>\cos2\theta=2\cos^2\theta-1</m>. The first two formula can be used to obtain the third formula:
        <me>
          \tan^2\theta=\frac{\sin^2\theta}{\cos^2\theta}=\frac{\dfrac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}}{\dfrac{1+\cos(2\theta)}{2}}=\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{1+\cos(2\theta)}
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write <m>\sin^4\theta</m> as an expression that does not involve powers of sine or cosine greater than 1.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We will use the Reducing Powers Formula twice.
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin^4\theta \amp = (\sin^2\theta)^2</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\left(\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\right)^2\amp \amp \mbox{reducing powers}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\frac{1}{4}\left(1-2\cos(2\theta)+\cos^2(2\theta)\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\frac{1}{4}\left(1-2\cos(2\theta)+\frac{1+\cos(4\theta)}{2}\right)\amp \amp \mbox{reducing powers}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\frac{1}{4}\left(1-2\cos(2\theta)+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{\cos(4\theta)}{2}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\frac{1}{4}\left(\frac{3}{2}-\frac{4}{2}\cos(2\theta)+\frac{1}{2}\cos(4\theta)\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\frac{1}{8}\left(3-4\cos(2\theta)+\cos(4\theta)\right)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Half-Angle Formulas</title>
    <p>
      Another set of useful formulas are the half-angle formulas.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-half-angle-formulas-sin-cos-tan">
      <title>Half-Angle Formulas</title><idx><h>Half-Angle Formulas</h><h>for Sine</h></idx>
      <idx><h>Half-Angle Formulas</h><h>for Cosine</h></idx>
      <idx><h>Half-Angle Formulas</h><h>for Tangent</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin\frac{\theta}{2}\amp =\pm\sqrt{\frac{1-\cos\theta}{2}},\amp \cos\frac{\theta}{2}\amp =\pm\sqrt{\frac{1+\cos\theta}{2}},\amp \tan\frac{\theta}{2}\amp =\pm\sqrt{\frac{1-\cos\theta}{1+\cos\theta}}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          The choice of the + or - sign depends on the Quadrant in which <m>\theta/2</m> lies.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        We take the square root on both sides of the Formulas for Reducing Powers (<xref ref="def-formula-reducing-powers"/>) and halve the angle (<m>\theta</m> becomes <m>\frac{\theta}{2}</m> and <m>2\theta</m> becomes <m>\theta</m>) to arrive at our formulas.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <example>
      <title>Locating ʻĀina</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We are now ready to revisit the problem posed at the start of this section when we were asked to determine the exact coordinates of the house ʻĀina on the Unit Circle.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We know the coordinates are at
          <me>
            (\cos22.5^{\circ},\sin22.5^{\circ})
          </me>.
          To find the exact value of <m>\cos22.5^{\circ}</m>, we will use the half-angle formula:
          <md>
            <mrow> \cos22.5^{\circ} \amp = \cos\left(\frac{45}{2}\right)^{\circ} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{1+\cos45^{\circ}}{2}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{1+\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}{2}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{\frac{2}{2}+\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}{2}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{2+\sqrt{2}}{4}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}\cdot\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
          </md>
          Since the half-angle formula has <m>\pm</m>, we check the quadrant. In this case, our angle is <m>22.5^{\circ}</m>, which is in Quadrant I. Therefore, we choose the positive value.
        </p>
        <p>
          Finding the exact value of <m>\sin22.5^{\circ}</m> is left for <xref ref="exer-half-angle-sin22_5"/>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="ex_half-angle">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Given <m>\sin\theta=-\frac{5}{13}</m> and <m>\theta</m> lies in Quadrant III, find the exact value of
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sin\frac{\theta}{2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Notice the Half-Angle Formulas all require us to know <m>\cos\theta</m>. Since the given information describes the same triangle in <xref ref="ex_double-angle"/>, we refer to that problem to get <m>\cos\theta=-\frac{12}{13}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Next, since <m>\theta</m> is in Quadrant III, <m>180^{\circ}\lt \theta\lt 270^{\circ}</m>,
            so dividing by 2 gives us <m>\frac{180^{\circ}}{2}\lt \frac{\theta}{2}\lt \frac{270^{\circ}}{2}</m> or <m>90^{\circ}\lt \frac{\theta}{2}\lt 135^{\circ}</m>.
            Therefore, we conclude that <m>\frac{\theta}{2}</m> lies in Quadrant II.
          </p>
          <p>
            To calculate <m>\sin\frac{\theta}{2}</m>,
            we first note that because <m>\frac{\theta}{2}</m> lies in Quadrant II,
            <m>\sin\frac{\theta}{2}>0</m> so we will choose the positive (+) sign in the Half-Angle Formula:
            <md>
              <mrow>\sin\frac{\theta}{2}\amp = \sqrt{\frac{1-\cos\theta}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{\frac{1-\left(-\frac{12}{13}\right)}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{\frac{1+\frac{12}{13}}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{\frac{\frac{13}{13}+\frac{12}{13}}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{\frac{\frac{25}{13}}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{\frac{25}{26}}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\cos\frac{\theta}{2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since <m>\frac{\theta}{2}</m> is in Quadrant II, we know that
            <m>\cos\frac{\theta}{2}\lt 0</m> so we will choose the negative (-) sign in the Half-Angle Formula:
            <md>
              <mrow>\cos\frac{\theta}{2}\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{1+\cos\theta}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{1+\left(-\frac{12}{13}\right)}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{1-\frac{12}{13}}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{\frac{13}{13}-\frac{12}{13}}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{\frac{1}{13}}{2}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{1}{26}}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\tan\frac{\theta}{2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since <m>\frac{\theta}{2}</m> is in Quadrant II, we know that
            <m>\tan\frac{\theta}{2}\lt 0</m> so we will choose the negative (-) sign in the Half-Angle Formula:
            <md>
              <mrow>\tan\frac{\theta}{2}\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{1-\cos\theta}{1+\cos\theta}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{1-\left(-\frac{12}{13}\right)}{1+\left(-\frac{12}{13}\right)}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{1+\frac{12}{13}}{1-\frac{12}{13}}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{\frac{13}{13}+\frac{12}{13}}{\frac{13}{13}-\frac{12}{13}}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{\frac{25}{13}}{\frac{1}{13}}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{\frac{25}{13}\cdot\frac{13}{1}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -\sqrt{25}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = -5</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </example>
    <p>
      We can derive another formula for <m>\tan\frac{\theta}{2}</m> that does not involve <m>\pm</m>:
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-half-angle-formula-tangent">
      <title>Half-Angle Formulas for Tangent</title><idx><h>Half-Angle Formulas</h><h>for Tangent</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <me>
            \tan\frac{\theta}{2}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{1-\cos\theta}{1+\cos\theta}}=\frac{1-\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}=\frac{\sin\theta}{1+\cos\theta}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        We begin by first multiplying both sides of the Sine formula for Reducing Powers by 2 and halving the angle:
        <me>
          1-\cos\theta=2\sin^2\left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right)
        </me>
        and applying the double-angle formula to:
        <me>
          \sin\theta=\sin2\cdot\frac{\theta}{2}=2\sin\frac{\theta}{2}\cos\frac{\theta}{2}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Dividing the two preceding results
        <me>
          \frac{1-\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}=\frac{2\sin^2\left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right)}{2\sin\frac{\theta}{2}\cos\frac{\theta}{2}}=\frac{\sin\frac{\theta}{2}}{\cos\frac{\theta}{2}}=\tan\frac{\theta}{2}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus
        <me>
          \tan\frac{\theta}{2}=\frac{1-\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Similarly, it can be shown that
        <me>
          \tan\frac{\theta}{2}=\frac{\sin\theta}{1+\cos\theta}
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate <m>\tan\frac{\theta}{2}</m> from <xref ref="ex_half-angle">Example</xref> using the above formula.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <me>
            \tan\frac{\theta}{2}=\frac{1-\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}=\frac{1-\left(-\frac{12}{13}\right)}{-\frac{5}{13}}=\frac{\frac{25}{13}}{-\frac{5}{13}}=\frac{25}{13}\cdot\left(-\frac{13}{5}\right)=-5
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      Note: We obtained the same result for <m>\tan\frac{\theta}{2}</m> as we did in <xref ref="ex_half-angle">Example</xref>. In this example, we did not have to determine if <m>\tan\frac{\theta}{2}</m> was positive or negative, however, we do need to know the values of both <m>\sin\theta</m> and <m>\cos\theta</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  

